From f04d5078a01a8d5d5476d17a2fb7d9fc87e07910 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: souliane <21343492+souliane@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Tue, 23 Jun 2026 11:45:33 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] feat(comment-density): flag restating comments and
 signature-echo docstrings

The advisory comment-density gate was line-count only: it counted
comment-only lines (ratio + consecutive run) but never inspected whether a
comment carried a non-obvious why or merely restated the code, and it
exempted docstring bodies entirely. So a single inline comment restating the
next code line, and a verbose docstring that just echoes the signature (the
data-migration style), both slipped through below the consecutive threshold.

Add content-aware detection to teatree.hooks.privacy_diff_comment_density:
a comment whose meaningful words merely restate the following code line's
identifier tokens (narration verb + tokens already in the code) flags on a
single line, and a docstring opening that merely echoes the function/class
name flags. A genuine non-obvious-why comment (words the code does not
contain) and a justified multi-line docstring stay allowed - abuse is
flagged, multi-line is not forced to single-line.

All three surfaces (pre-push hook, CI job, t3 tool comment-density) and the
golden corpus share report_diff, so one change strengthens them together.

Wire comments-as-code (names + types are the docs; a long comment is a code
smell -> refactor) crisply into the t3:code skill and the coder agent brief,
and pin the two real abuse patterns in the golden corpus plus a new
anti-vacuous behavioral eval (comment_density_no_restating_docstring_or_inline).
